flowRoot.flowPara: The original UI of the game was difficult for kids to get used to, and the original store menu only had bulk items which were complicated to calculate. The recipe of the Lemonade couldn't be changed and one would unrealistically sell all of their lemonade that the weather permitted. The game was also limited to Lemonade and English, which aren't the most international concepts for children to get used to.

Lastly, we created an activity called Sash for the XO laptops which could display the badges and achievments acquired during gameplay. The badges are locally stored and are awarded once a set of conditions are met. Though originally implemented for Lemonade Stand, the Sash activity reads from the XO's datastore and can award badges for any XO software.

We started by analyzing educational games for the XO Laptops created by RIT students a couple of years ago. This game, Lemonade Stand, was designed to show and teach children the basic business, microeconomic, and math skills involved in running a Lemonade Stand. After playtesting it a bit ourselves, we brought the game to a local middleschool for the youth to playtest as well on National Lemonade day.
